The people of Macedonia took part in a referendum on Sunday to decide whether the country would be renamed the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would overturn a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked the country's bid for European Union and NATO membership.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbor represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its accession to NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's Slavic majority population.
President George Ivanov has said he will not participate in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether turnout will reach the required 50 percent for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot paper was: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU by accepting the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to seek membership in organizations such as the EU and NATO for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I came today to vote for the future of the country, so that the youth of Macedonia can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because then our lives will all be safer", said Olivera Georgievska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, several members of Parliament have said they will abide by the outcome of the vote to make it final.
A two-thirds majority in Parliament is required to change the name.
The state election commission said there were no reports of irregularities as of 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when it gave the current 66 percent of registered voters.
"I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", said Jose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital, Skopje.
The Prime Minister of Macedonia, Zoraf Zaev, his wife Zorika and son Dusko voted in the referendum on the country's name change that would pave the way for the country's accession to NATO and the European Union in the city of Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
In front of the Parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov sets up a small tent and sets up chairs in front of tents set up by those who will boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads held high, not as second-class partners", Kavardakov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia, and become a member of the Eurasian Union".
Prime Minister Zaev said that NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
"I believe the overwhelming majority will be in favour, as over 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO", Zaev said after voting.
He said that a positive result would be "a confirmation of our future".
According to a poll published last Monday by the Institute for Political Research of Macedonia, the referendum would have a turnout of 30 to 43 percent, which is below the required turnout.
