John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a history of academic excellence, which continued in 2018, with yet another string of outstanding test scores, which were only further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, the arts, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible level of service to pupils and their parents.
The aim of independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and higher levels of education, the careers they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a bespoke school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, then what you say goes into their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say goes to his heart".
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot simply rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on recent results of this year's exams, we find that languages are at the top of the performance charts, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved an A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved A grades in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also had A grades.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages today, as an elective subject, are considered as important as subjects related to science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 UK Employment and Skills Commission survey revealed that, as to the reasons employers had difficulty filling job vacancies, a rate of 17 percent was related to a lack of language skills.
The need to acquire language skills is therefore becoming increasingly urgent in order to prepare young people for their future professional careers.
As more future job opportunities require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future because of this skill that you can use throughout your life.
If someone is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically that multilingual person will have an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, while French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of respondents (15 percent).
That is why investing in language learning today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered more important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be some languages to choose from in independent schools, which have specialised language teachers.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It cannot be denied that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of a country, and this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered truly 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for Scotland's young people.
They have to.
John Edward is a director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
