North Korea says it won't disarm unilaterally without confidence-building measures.
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions deepen distrust of the United States and that his country will not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual general assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" in the past year, such as halting nuclear and ballistic tests, dismantling nuclear test facilities and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we are not seeing any response from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances there is no way to unilaterally initiate our disarmament".
While Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea will be rewarded as it progresses in the process, his statement was significant in that it did not completely rule out unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint communiqué of Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit held between an acting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first "surrender" its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for easing of tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on denuclearization first and increases pressure by threatening sanctions to achieve its goal by blackmailing, obstructing even the declaration of the end of the war", Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of those who don't know us.
But the problem is that the continuing sanctions are deepening our distrust".
Ri made no mention of a planned second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader pointed out at the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister, however, pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: "If the partner on the issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end".
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the US mainland with North Korean ballistic missiles was inevitable because "Bad President" Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving forward with disarmament measures, but said more still needed to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timeline for it, saying, "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue intensively and uninterruptedly until full, final and confirmed denuclearisation is achieved".
The Security Council unanimously approved sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to neutralize funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
