The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eliminate poverty by increasing the number of those actively fighting against it.
To secure a free ticket to the event (unless they were willing to buy a VIP ticket), participants had to complete a series of missions or "actions", such as registering as a volunteer, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or finding other meaningful ways to help raise awareness about their goal of eradicating poverty.
But how successful is Global Citizen, with 12 years left to achieve its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding a free concert the right way to convince our fellow citizens to take action or is it just another case of so-called "click activism", where someone feels they are really making a difference by signing an e-petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, the Global Citizen group reports that it has recorded more than 19 million "actions" from its supporters, promoting a range of different causes.
It reports that these actions have helped world leaders announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which are set to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group reported 390 commitments and announcements as a result of these actions, of which at least USD 10 billion have already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that secured funds have so far directly affected nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key pledges include The Power of Nutrition, a British association of investors and implementers who have made a commitment to "help children reach their full potential", pledging to give Rwanda $35 million to eradicate malnutrition, having received over 4,700 tweets from members of the Global Citizens community.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and members of the Global Citizens community like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition a footnote in history", Tracy Ullman, ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, told the audience during the live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that following more than 5,000 actions calling on the UK to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project called The Power of Nutrition, which targets 5 million women and children with nutritional interventions.
In response to the question "What makes you think we can eradicate extreme poverty?" included in the website's FAQ,
One member of the Global Citizen community responded: "The road ahead will be long and hard, and sometimes we will fall and fail.
But like all the great human rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because united we are stronger.
