One of his grandchildren, Michael Van, said it was "highly symbolic" that the plaque's unveiling took place exactly 100 years after his grandfather's heroic deed for which he received the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918 Lieutenant-Colonel Van led his battalion into the Seine-Cendon Canal in the midst of very thick fog and while receiving heavy fire from battle guns and machine guns".
Later, he rushed to the front line and with "exceptional bravery" led the line forward, before striking alone with a three-gun battle rifle from the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, almost a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather's heroic deeds were "something I know I could never reach, it's something that makes you feel boundless respect".
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, also laid a wreath after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said he was "very honoured to be part of the parade" and added that "the bravery of a true hero is proven by the support he has from many people".
MMA fans stayed up late to watch Bellator 206, but they saw Peppa Pig.
Consider this scenario: You have been up all night watching the thrilling Bellator 206, but you are deprived of the joy of watching this unique sporting event.
The San Jose schedule included 13 matches, including six on the main card, and was to be shown live in the UK, by Channel 5, in the night-time zone.
At 6:00 a.m., as Geoghard Musashi and Rory McDonald prepared to step into the ring, viewers in the UK were stunned when the show changed to Peppa Pig.
Some were not happy at all, having stayed up until the early hours of the morning especially for the race.
One Twitter fan described the screening of the children's program as "some kind of sick joke".
"By law, this content was not appropriate for 6 a.m., so the children's program had to be shown", said Dave Swartz, senior vice president of marketing and communications at Bellator, when asked about the broadcast.
"Peppa the Pig, yes".
Bellator president Scott Coker said the program was being edited to include UK viewers in the future.
"If we think about the replay, I think we can do it", Coker said.
"But it's six o'clock Sunday morning there and we won't be able to do it until Sunday our time, which is their Monday.
But we're trying.
Believe me, when the switch happened, there was a lot of back-and-forth texting, and it wasn't friendly.
We tried to fix it, we thought it was a technical error.
It wasn't, it was because of the regulations.
I promise you, next time, it won't happen.
We're gonna limit it to five games instead of six, like we usually do, and we tried to give the fans more, and we went too far.
It's an unpleasant situation".
Tom Daley felt "inferior" because of his sexuality
Olympic diving champion Tom Daley said he grew up feeling inferior to others because of his sexuality, however, it drove him to succeed.
The 24-year-old said that he didn't realize until high school that "not everyone is like me".
Speaking on the first Desert Island Discs hosted by Lauren Laverne on Radio 4, she said she supported gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that since becoming a parent, he is less interested in winning the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, a regular on the popular radio show, had been on sick leave for several months.
As a guest on Laverne's first show, Daley said that he felt "inadequate" compared to others when he was growing up because "it was not socially acceptable to like someone both boys and girls".
He said: "To this day, those feelings of inferiority and difference give me the strength and will to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was "something", he said, so he wouldn't disappoint anyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist is a prominent advocate for the rights of the LGBTQ community and used his participation in this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he decided to speak out because he felt lucky to be able to live freely, without consequences, and that he wanted to give others "hope".
The three-time world champion said it was "a surprise" when she fell in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom she met in 2013.
Daly married Oscar winner Dustin Lance Black last year, who is 20 years his senior, but he has maintained that age difference has never been an issue.
"When you go through so much at such a young age" (he competed in his first Olympics at age 14, while his father died of cancer three years later) "it's hard to find a peer who has similar ups and downs".
The couple adopted a son in June, Robert Ray Black-Daily, and Daley said it changed "his whole outlook".
"If you ask me last year, all I wanted was to win the gold medal", he said.
"But there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.
His son shares the same name as his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at age 40 of brain cancer.
Daley said his father couldn't accept the fact that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they had tickets for the 2012 Olympics in London, as he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him, 'Daddy, you won't be around to sit in the front row,'" she said.
"I held his hand as he stopped breathing and only when he stopped breathing and was dead did I finally accept that he was not invincible", she said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won the bronze medal.
"I knew it was what I had dreamed of all my life, to compete in diving at the Olympics in my homeland, there was no better feeling", she said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song, Heather Small's Proud, which cheered him up as he prepared for the Olympics and still gives him the creeps.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 every Sunday at 11:15 BST.
The out-of-shape Mickelson will be sitting on the bench Saturday at the Ryder Cup.
American Phil Mickelson will set a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he'll have to improve his performance to avoid being remembered for the wrong reasons.
Mickelson, competing for a record 12th time in the biennial event, was forced by captain Jim Furyk to sit on the bench for Saturday's fourball and foursome.
Instead of being the center of the action, as is customary for the United States, the five-time winner has divided the day cheering from the lines and working on his game in the hope of fixing his problem areas.
With no straightforward driver ever to emerge even at the peak of his career, the 48-year-old's game is not suited to the cramped course of Le Golf National, where long-distance runs are often problematic.
And as if the difficulty of the court wasn't enough, Mickelson, in Sunday's ninth match, faces Francesco Molinari, British Open champion, who is teaming up with rookie Tommy Fleetwood to win all four of their matches this week.
If the Americans, who were four points behind in the opening 12 singles, can take the lead with a good start, Mickelson's play could be crucial.
Furyk expressed confidence in his player, not that he could say anything else.
"He fully understood the role he was playing today, he patted me on the back, put his arm around me and said he would be ready for tomorrow", Furik said.
"He has a lot of confidence.
His name is in the Hall of Fame and he's given so much to these teams, both in the past and this week.
I guess I didn't count on him playing two games.
I was thinking more, but that's where we ended up and so we felt we had to go.
He wants to go out there like everybody else".
Mickelson will beat Nick Faldo's record for most Sunday games in the Ryder Cup.
It could mark the end of a Ryder Cup career that didn't match his individual record.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven half-centuries, although Furik said his presence had benefits for the team.
"He's funny, sarcastic, witty, likes to make jokes and is excellent in the team room", he explained.
"I think the younger players were also having fun teasing him this week.
His contribution is not only in the game".
European team captain Thomas Bjorn knows that the big lead could be lost soon.
Thomas Bjorn, the captain of the European team, knows from experience that a big lead starting with the singles on the final day of the Ryder Cup can easily turn into a loss.
The Dane made his debut in the 1997 race at Valderrama, where a team led by Seve Ballesteros managed to gain a five-point lead over the Americans, but barely managed to cross the finish line by a chest gap, winning 141⁄2- 131⁄2.
"You keep reminding yourself that we had a big lead at Valderrama, we had a big lead at Brookline, where we lost, and at Valderrama, where we won, but barely", Bjorn said, pictured, after watching the 2018 generation win 5-3 both Friday and yesterday and lead 10-6 at Le Golf National.
So history will show me and all the members of the team that this is not over.
We're going out tomorrow to give it all.
We're gonna go out there and play it right.
Nothing's over until you see the grades on the board.
We have one goal, to win this trophy, and that's what we're focused on.
I always say that I'm focused on the 12 players on our team, but we know very well that there are equally good players on the other team, the best in the world".
Satisfied with his players' performance on a difficult golf course, Bjorn adds: "I wouldn't rush to predict the outcome.
Tomorrow is another beast.
Tomorrow, it's all about individual performance, and that's something else.
It's great to be on the court with a teammate when things are going well, but when you're out there by yourself, that's when you put your golfing skills to the test.
That's the message you need to get to the players, how to bring out their best selves tomorrow.
You leave your teammate behind and he has to give his all and show his best".
Unlike Bjorn, Jim Furyk of the opposing team will ask his players to score better individual performances than they did with their teammates, except for Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who won three points out of four.
Furyk himself has experienced both ends of the last day's upsets, as he was part of the winning team in Brookline before the unexpected defeat as Europe performed its miracle.
"I remember every word he said", he replied when asked how Ben Crenshaw, the 1999 captain, had rallied his players for the final day.
"We have 12 big games tomorrow, but we want a quick start like Brookline, like Medinah.
When we get that momentum, there's a lot of pressure in the midfield.
We decide our order accordingly and play in the order that suits us, we'll try to do our magic tomorrow".
Thomas has taken over the lead of the race and faces Rory McIlroy in the top game, with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, John Rum, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, the rest of the Europeans in the top half of the line.
"I went with this group in this order because I think it covers the whole route", Björn said justifying his choices for singles.
New postponement for Germany's new warship
The new German Navy frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War-era warships, but it won't be delivered until next year at least, due to faulty systems and soaring costs, local media reports.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, citing a spokesman for the armed forces.
The ship was supposed to have joined the Navy in 2014, but delivery problems were critical to the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the older Bremen-class frigates.
They'll carry a powerful cannon, a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature is that the frequency of maintenance work is reduced, as the new frigates will be able to be used for up to two years outside German ports.
However, the continuing delays mean that while the warships are considered state-of-the-art, allowing Germany to show off its power abroad, by the time they are finally put into service, they will already be outdated, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipyard since the surrender.
Not much information has been released on the reasons for the return, but German media reported a number of significant "defects in software and hardware" that would render the warship unusable if used on a combat mission.
The software problems were particularly significant as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships have a crew of about 120 sailors, barely half as many as the older Bremen class frigates.
It was also revealed that the ship has a much greater weight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-ton frigate Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to weigh twice as much as the similar class of ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the faulty equipment, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) was also an issue.
It is said to have reached a paltry €3.1 billion (3.6 billion euros), while the original budget was €2.2 billion.
The problems plaguing the new frigates are particularly significant as Germany's naval power shrinks.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, admitted that the navy "will soon be without ships for missions".
The official said the problem has grown over time because the old ships have been decommissioned, but there are no other ships to replace them.
It claimed that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could be accepted into the Navy.
The National Trust is eavesdropping on the secret lives of bats
New research conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting for food.
The findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to design future actions to protect the environment.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will investigate the habits of the common nano-bat and the micro-bat, as well as the brown-headed bat and the Dobbedoon's flying squirrel in Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld sensors.
Analyzing the sound of all the recordings by experts will determine the frequency of the bats' calls, as well as which species have this behavior.
A habitat map and a report will then be created to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on landscape scales.
Rob Dewar, environmental counselor for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management, such as creating grasslands and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly since the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development projects that affect their nesting sites and destroy their habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting are also a danger, as are fly-tape and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes in catching their prey.
They use a sophisticated sonication technique to spot insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land throughout the country, considers bats very important.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, inspect bat nests, and sometimes rescue them.
The organisation has also set up Scotland's first and only bat sanctuary exclusively at Threave Farm, in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says the property is ideal for bats.
"Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats", he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of big trees and an ideal habitat.
There is still much we don't know about bats, so the work we are doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to grow their populations".
It stresses that it is important to check for bats before any home maintenance work, as destroying a single nest of young could kill up to 400 females and young, potentially wiping out the entire local population.
Bats are protected species and it is forbidden to kill them, harass them or disturb their peace, or destroy their nests.
Elizabeth Ferrell, head of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, encouraged the public to volunteer their help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species we just don't know the evolution of their population".
Ronaldo denies rape allegations as his lawyers prepare to sue German magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo has described the rape allegations against him as "fake news", saying that some "want to promote themselves" by using his name.
His lawyers are going to sue the German news magazine Der Spiegel, which published the allegations.
The Portugal and Juventus forward is accused of raping an American woman named Catherine Majorca in a Las Vegas hotel room in 2009.
