Brexit: UK 'will forever regret' loss of car industry
The UK "will regret it forever" if it loses its reputation as a global leader in the automotive industry after Brexit, said Business Secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK told the BBC that if Britain leaves the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at its plant in Barnaston, near Derby.
"We need an agreement", Mr Clark said.
The Japanese car industry said the impact of cross-border delays in a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The plant in Bernaston, where Toyota's Auris and Avensis models are manufactured, produced almost 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"My view is that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our plant will stop", said Marvin Cook, Toyota's chief executive in Burnaston.
Other carmakers in the UK have also expressed fears of leaving the EU without a deal on cross-border trade, such as Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, has said it will close its Mini factory in Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concerns concern the supply chain risks according to the car manufacturers in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line follows just-in-time, with spare parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in both the UK and EU for custom-built cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, there could be problems at the border, resulting in delays and shortages of parts according to the industry.
It would be impossible for Toyota to keep stock beyond one day at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, so production would stop.
Mr Clarke said that Mrs May's plan for the future relationship with the EU 'is specifically about solving the issue of border controls'.
"We need a deal, we want the best deal possible that will allow us not only to have a temporary success, but also to take advantage of this opportunity", he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"The evidence coming not only from Toyota but also from other manufacturers is that it is imperative to ensure continuity in supply chains".
Toyota was unable to say for how long it would stop production, however, it warned that in the long run the additional costs would reduce the factory's competitiveness and ultimately cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at Bernaston for 24 years and is Unite's union manager at the factory, said union members are increasingly worried: "From my experience, if these jobs are lost, they are never going to come back.
A government spokesman said: 'We have presented a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU.'
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein may be delayed again, White House announces
Donald Trump's landmark meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein may be "delayed by another week" as the fight for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian election interference, the connections of Trump aides with Russia, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
The possibility that Trump would fire the deputy attorney general, jeopardizing Mueller's independence, has been fueling Washington's rumours for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein discussed wearing a wire in order to record his conversations with Trump and allow for the president's removal under the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied the report.
However, last Monday he went to the White House amid reports that he was going to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was then at the United Nations in New York, was announced for Thursday.
Trump said he "would rather" not fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was delayed to avoid coinciding with a hearing before the Senate Judiciary Committee in which Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual harassment, Dr. Christine Blazy Ford, testified.
On Friday, Trump ordered the FBI to conduct an investigation within a week into the allegations against Kavanaugh, further delaying the Senate vote.
Sarah Sanders, Trump's spokeswoman, appeared on Fox News Sunday.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, he said: "No date has been set yet, maybe this week, but maybe another week given all the other cases in the Supreme Court.
But we'll see, I always like to keep the press informed".
Some journalists have disputed this claim: Sanders has not held a White House press conference since September 10.
Host Chris Wallace asked why this is happening.
Sanders responded that the limited frequency of the news was not due to a dislike of the "impression" moves of television journalists, although she said: "I won't disagree with the fact that they are shown".
Then he hinted that there would be increased or direct communication between Trump and the press.
"The president gives more interviews than any previous president", he said, adding without citing evidence: "We looked at those numbers".
Updates will continue to be conducted, Sanders said, but "if the press is able to ask questions directly to the President of the United States, that's incomparably better than talking to me.
We're trying to do it often and you've seen that we've done it often in the last few weeks and it will take the place of the press release where you can talk to the president of the United States".
Trump often receives questions when he leaves the White House or participates in open meetings or press conferences with official guests.
Private press conferences are rare.
This week in New York, the president seems to have shown why this is the case, with an unconventional and sometimes bizarre appearance before a gathering of reporters.
The Health Secretary sends a letter to EU citizens working in Scotland's National Health Service amid fears over Brexit
The Minister for Health has sent a letter to EU citizens employed in the Scottish National Health System to express the country's gratitude and to wish them to remain after the UK leaves the European Union.
Jean Freeman, a Scottish MP, sent a letter less than six months before the UK leaves the EU.
The Scottish Government has already committed to cover the costs of applying for settled status for EU citizens working in its devolved public services.
Mrs Freeman wrote: 'The UK-EU negotiations on withdrawal continued over the summer and are on track for expected decisions in the autumn.
However, the UK Government has also stepped up preparations for a possible no-deal scenario.
I know this must be a very difficult time for all of you.
