Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp fee for buying property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp fee for buying property in the UK, with the extra money used to help the homeless, according to new Tory plans.
The measure would neutralize the success of Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters.
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on buyers who do not pay taxes in the UK
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp fee to buy property in the UK, with the extra money used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
The measure will be seen as an attempt to undermine the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters with promises of more affordable housing and targeting higher wages.
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on natural and legal persons not taxed in the UK, and the additional money will boost the government's campaign to fight homelessness.
The increase in the current stamp fee, together with the higher tax rates introduced two years ago for the purchase of second homes and rental homes, may amount to three percent.
The Treasury expects the measure to generate up to 120 million pounds a year.
An estimated 13 per cent of newly built properties in London are bought by non-UK residents, leading to higher prices and making it more difficult for first-time home buyers to enter the property market.
Many affluent areas of the country - especially the capital - have become "ghost towns" because of the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time abroad.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in stamp duty so more young people can buy their first home.
He accused big construction companies of keeping property prices high by buying land without using it and called on Mrs May to remove ceilings on affordable housing to restore Britain's "housing disgrace".
Mr Corbyn announced a series of impressive proposed housing reforms, including rent controls and a ban on evictions "without fault".
It also wants to give councils more power to build new homes.
Mrs May said: "Last year I said I would devote my prime ministership to restoring the British dream - to improving lives for each new generation.
And that means fixing the broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and make a life here.
However, it would not be right for non-UK residents and companies based abroad to buy homes as easily as hardworking British nationals.
For too many people the dream of homeownership has become too far away and the indignity of homelessness remains".
Jack Ross: "My ultimate ambition is to coach the Scotland team"
Sunderland captain Jack Ross says his "absolute ambition" is to one day coach the Scotland national team.
The 42-year-old Scot is excited about the challenge of resurrecting the north-east England side, who are currently in third place in League One, three points below the top.
He moved to the Stadium of Light in the summer, having previously brought St Mirren back to the Scottish Premiership the previous season.
"I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I got a call up for the second national team and that was it", Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound radio show.
"But I grew up watching the Scottish team in Hampden all the time with my dad as a kid, and that's something that always drew me back.
But this opportunity will only come if I succeed in coaching teams".
Among Ross' predecessors at Sunderland are Dick Advocate, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paolo DiCanio. He has also played for the United States national team.
The former Alloa Athletic manager says he was not shocked to be asked to succeed such established names at such a big club, having previously turned down approaches from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Right now success for me will be measured by answering the question 'can I bring this team back to the Premier League?'
Because of the structure and facilities of this team, it is undoubtedly a Premier League club", he said.
"It's not an easy job to get there, but I'll probably only consider myself successful here if I can get the team back there".
