The following are some important facts about Palu and Dongala, on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, located at the edge of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 inhabitants in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami hit.
Dongala is a sub-kingdom that stretches along more than 300 kilometres (180 mi) of coastline in the southwest of Sulawesi Island.
The county, a tier of administrative division below the province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main mainstays of the economy in Central Sulawesi province and particularly in the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is most common in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Dongola have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938 a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Dongala.
A tsunami also struck western Dongala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismic Ring of Fire in the Pacific Ocean and is frequently hit by earthquakes.
Some of the largest recent earthquakes and tsunamis are as follows:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26 caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coastline, with over half in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late May and early April.
Hundreds dead on Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake hits southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: An earthquake measuring 7.6 on the Richter scale centred near the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake hits one of the Medawi Islands, near Sumatra, causing a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A low-sequence earthquake hits the Pindi Jaya region of the Czech Republic, causing devastation and panic as it brings back memories of the devastation wrought by the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
